name: Kaiser Permanente Canyon Crest Mental Health Offices
review_text:
I was initially nervous about my appointment here after reading some of the concerning reviews, worried I might not receive the care I needed. However, my experience was the complete opposite. Dr. Kim took extra time during my appointment to thoroughly understand my experiences, current challenges, and future goals. He listened attentively, clarified things that I was not aware of or didn't fully understand, gave me some life advice that truly hit the mark, and created a treatment plan that will hopefully lead to better outcomes over time.

Rather than just focusing on medication, he took a comprehensive approach, considering both my mental health and overall well-being while emphasizing the importance of thoughtful adjustments. I left feeling truly heard and cared for, far exceeding my expectations.

Shout out to Dr. Kim. Thank you for all that you do!

The therpaist Patricia is immersive; kind, patient, and PROACTIVE. Very refreshing. The hispanic lady at check in was very kind and softspoken not shouting ?'s AT you, very kind. I also witnessed quite a few interactions with other walkins and patients both adult and children and the feedback is all positive! Until after9a.m. when 2 women came in to their front desk window and complained aloud about some meetings and work policies etc..they really should just focus on the work..take your gripes to mngmt.
If you're referred here, I understand there've been a lot of updates and changes to this part of Kaiser's behavioral health. Give it a shot. üëç

name: Kaiser Permanente Canyon Crest Mental Health Offices
review_text: $167 for a 30 minute phone call with a rude psychiatrist who clearly didn‚Äôt care ?  I wanted to come in for a ‚Äúin person‚Äù Therapy session was only offered over the phone with a rude lady who began to raise her voice and become audibly annoyed because I didn‚Äôt understand her or why I couldn‚Äôt be seen in person.  Was previously seen in person for a 60minute session approx $80 through Kaiser at a different location, now all of a sudden it‚Äôs twice the price for half the time and none of the customer service ? For someone seeking help with dealing with difficult times this was a very unpleasant experience that left me feeling worse off. Should have been free considering all she did was go over The paperwork I filled out and referred me elsewhere.

name: Kaiser Permanente Canyon Crest Mental Health Offices
review_text: I‚Äôm currently on the waiting list for another psychiatrist, but my prior one was just not working. They were very surface level when it came to our conversations. I finally got the courage to talk about my eating disorder behaviors and he told me to ‚Äúlose weight‚Äù, and didn‚Äôt bother referring me to a specialist. Mind you I don‚Äôt have binge eating disorder, so there was no reason for him to say that. It was very upsetting. I‚Äôm now in eating disorder group therapy because I had to call the office and tell them everything. Overall, I have not really been having a great experience, but at least im getting a bit of help.

review_text:
It is very upsetting to see how Kaiser‚Äôs protocol is - when someone with depression really needs their help and they are not really being listened.

My wife is going through a very difficult time right now that to tell you the truth, I am very concerned about her that I begged her to seek for help.

I finally got her to listen to me to see a doctor, which I thought would be the best thing for her.  However, today she saw the doctor and they had nothing to say ‚Äì only to take MEDICATION and she would be able to RETURN TO WORK.
How can that possible? That absurd!!! How can she very ready to return to work? When she is a mess. She could hardly make it at home, how you expect her to do her job. She cannot be by herself.  Is that what Kaiser Doctors are trained to do? Harming people instead of helping them. It is very disappointing. I thought telling her to go see a doctor was the best for her, but now I see the doctors have failed her and I have failed her as well.
This is just putting her in a bad place. Putting her up to failure maybe even losing her job or worst. I hope I can do something else for her because I see Kaiser will not do anything .All they had to do was listen on what she needs.

name: Kaiser Permanente Canyon Crest Mental Health Offices
review_text: After worrying about a member who is going through a very rough time, he stated he liked and was happy with his psychiatrist. He thought she really cared and was concerned about him. She threw meds at him and berated him for non-compliance. She said he didn't pick up his medications or take them properly. But said she still worried about him told him to come in at any time as she was concerned.  After an emergency visit (per her request) she saw him but rudely and firmly said she would not see him again under that sort of circumstance. He kept a scheduled appointment with her 3 months later, complying with her recommendations, and she dumped him as a patient suggesting he get a "second opinion". He is in crisis and she dismissed him without warning. In my opinion she was very unprofessional.

name: Kaiser Permanente Canyon Crest Mental Health Offices
review_text:
Trying to schedule an appointment within a reasonable amount of time is a joke. I wanted to change doctors because I wasn't happy with the one I have, and the wait is FOUR months. If I stayed with my previous doctor the wait is still THREE months.

And not to mention trying to speak with a real person at this place takes about 25-30 minutes of hold time, every single time I call. When I finally got through to a person, they gave me an appointment for March. I called back the following week to see if any openings had come up, and the lady on the phone tells me I didn't even have an appointment scheduled. So the last lady didn't put me in the system and forced my appointment all the way out to APRIL!

The only way to get services faster is if you have a psychiatric emergency. What about the people who aren't at that point yet but still are in serious need of help? At the rate this office works, if you're a new patient, expect to get to the point of a psychiatric emergency before they will help you.

This is the worst psych department I've ever dealt with. I had more efficient service when I was covered through state medi-cal. And that's really sad to say.

name: Kaiser Permanente Canyon Crest Mental Health Offices
review_text:
TERRIBLE

My husband went in because he believes he has ADD. It took him YEARS to finally do something about it with my help because he kept procrastinating on it even though it was something he really wants to try fixing. Finally, even though I don't believe in pills for ADD I helped him make an appointment and now I wish I'd gone WITH HIM. I assumed this place would take care of him and they hadn't. They gave him medication for depression AFTER TELLING HIM HE HAS ADD! Why is he being given medication for depression? He had to go to some OTHER office to get medication! This is ridiculous we are going with Blue Cross for him now and abandoning Kaiser. I knew he shouldn't of signed up with Kaiser. Glad I work in the medical field so I can tell everyone to stay AWAY FROM KAISER INSURANCES. They don't do anything short of make a 1-2 step process a 5-7 step process just so they can bill the insurances for multiple visits.

Can't wait to walk in tomorrow and figure out how this got so screwed up.
